astrophe.Based mainly on archival records of the countries that carried out the forced migrations and of the international humanitarian organizations that tried but failed to prevent the disastrous results, Orderly and Humane: The Expulsion of the Germans after the Second World War is an authoritative and objective account. It examines an aspect of European history that few have wished to confront, exploring how the expulsions were conceived, planned, and executed and how their legacy reverberates throughout central Europe today. The book is an important study of the largest recorded episode of what we now call "ethnic cleansing," and it may also be the most significant untold story of the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aForced migrationxHistoryx20th centuryxCzech Republic. 0aForced migrationzCzech RepublicxHistoryy20th century. 0aGermansxHistoryx20th centuryxCzech RepublicxSudetenland. 0aGermanszCzech RepubliczSudetenlandxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopulation transfersxGermansxHistoryx20th century. 0aPopulation transfersxGermansxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xForced repatriation. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300183764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300183764.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles